---
title: The Implement Trap in GitHub Coding Agents
description: >-
  Why GitHub's coding agents ignore your custom workflow instructions and how to
  fix it
date: 2026-02-12
published: true
---
When you assign an issue to GitHub Copilot's coding agent, the system wraps your issue content inside a standard template that says *"Implement the necessary changes to the repository so that the requirements specified in the problem\_statement are met."* Your issue body, including any `<agent_instructions>`, gets nested inside that frame.

I hit this today. My `<agent_instructions>` said "after creating the initial PR, run [x] skill" instead of jumping straight to code. The agent ignored it. It prioritized the outer "Implement" directive and went straight to coding.

When I asked the agent to analyze what went wrong, it was clear: two competing instructions, and the outer frame won. The `<agent_instructions>` tag was *inside* the problem statement, so it competed with the outer directive rather than overriding it. The agent's built-in "Steps to Follow" (explore → test → implement) further reinforced the implementation bias.

One fix is to make your `<agent_instructions>` loud enough to break through the outer frame. The formula:

```
STOP + [what NOT to do] + [exact skill to invoke] + [how to invoke it] + [acknowledge the conflict]
```

The key insight: brevity and directness win under competing instruction pressure. Start with STOP, name the skill explicitly, list forbidden actions, and acknowledge the conflict head-on.

But a fair warning: this doesn't always work. And if you reliably need something to work the way you intend, a better solution may be to spin up your own agents (leveraging the various SDKs) inside of GitHub Actions. You can dispatch your instructions to them, where they won't have the weight of pre-encoded GitHub platform instructions wrapping them.
